vakia, and also among Rusyns. Compare   Pap   and   Pop  ."]}]},{"name":"Einion","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish (Tyrone): variant of   Moynihan  .","French: occupational name for a miner, from a diminutive of <i>minier</i> ‘miner’ (see   Minier  ). This surname is very rare in France; in North America it may thus (also) be an altered form of some other similar (like-sounding) French surname, such as   Mignon  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Moynihan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Patrick James, Donal, Eamon, Finbarr, Kieran, Niall.","Irish:","Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Muimhneacháin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Muimhneachán</i>’, a diminutive of the byname <i>Muimhneach</i> ‘Munsterman’, i.e. someone belonging to the province of Munster. In Mayo this surname has sometimes been translated into English as   Munster  . There has been some confusion with   Monaghan  ."]}]},{"name":"Gruffudd","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old Welsh <i>Grip(p)iud</i>, from an unexplained first element + a second element meaning ‘lord, prince’.  Gruffydd ap Llewelyn  (  d. 1063 ) was one of the most able rulers of Wales in the Middle Ages, scoring notable victories over the English until he was eventually defeated by  King Harold  in  1063 ."],"variants":[{"name":"Griffudd","meanings":["From Old Welsh <i>Grip(p)iud</i>, from an unexplained first element + a second element meaning ‘lord, prince’.  Gruffydd ap Llewelyn  (  d. 1063 ) was one of the most able rulers of Wales in the Middle Ages, scoring notable victories over the English until he was eventually defeated by  King Harold  in  1063 ."]},{"name":"Gruffud","meanings":["From Old Welsh <i>Grip(p)iud</i>, from an unexplained first element + a second element meaning ‘lord, prince’.  Gruffydd ap Llewelyn  (  d. 1063 ) was one of the most able